   111→includes the Rust logo SVG image found in the `images` directory at the same level as this file:
   127→## Extensions
   128→
   129→mdBook has several extensions beyond the standard CommonMark specification.
   131→### Strikethrough
   132→
   133→Text may be rendered with a horizontal line through the center by wrapping the
   134→text with one or two tilde characters on each side:
   146→### Footnotes
   147→
   148→A footnote generates a small numbered link in the text which when clicked
   149→takes the reader to the footnote text at the bottom of the item. The footnote
   150→label is written similarly to a link reference with a caret at the front. The
   151→footnote text is written like a link reference definition, with the text
   152→following the label. Example:
   171→### Tables
   172→
   173→Tables can be written using pipes and dashes to draw the rows and columns of
   174→the table. These will be translated to HTML table matching the shape. Example:
   191→### Task lists
   192→
   193→Task lists can be used as a checklist of items that have been completed.
   194→Example:
   208→### Smart punctuation
   209→
   210→Some ASCII punctuation sequences will be automatically turned into fancy Unicode
   211→characters:
   231→### Heading attributes
   232→
   233→Headings can have a custom HTML ID and classes. This lets you maintain the same ID even if you change the heading's text, it also lets you add multiple classes in the heading.
   244→### Definition lists
   245→
   246→Definition lists can be used for things like glossary entries. The term is listed on a line by itself, followed by one or more definitions. Each definition must begin with a `:` (after 0-2 spaces).
   279→### Admonitions
   280→
   281→An admonition is a special type of callout or notice block used to highlight important information. It is written as a blockquote with a special tag on the first line.
